## How can you contribute?

You can contribute to this documentation by following the link to this repository by clicking on the button "Edit on Github" in the top right corner of a page.
Before you start editing, please keep the following things in mind:

- The documentation is generally written in markdown. For most common practices that are supported on documentation platforms, you can take a look [here](https://commonmark.org/help/)

- Linking to other files can be done relatively. You can also link to URLs. The shown text is placed between square brackets \[ \] and the link or relative location is put behind it between parentheses \( \). 

    ```
        [This is the shown text](https://www.bing.com)
    ```
    
    which results in

    [This is the shown text](https://www.bing.com)
  
- To display images properly, it is recommended to use the following syntax:
    ```
    ![](data:image/png;base64,<base64 string without quotes>)
    ```
- It is possible to uses basic markup in tables, such as codeblocks (starting and ending with three backticks), alignment (by using `:--` for left aligned, `:--:` for center aligned and `---:` for right aligned in the line below the headers of the table). It is possible to use basic markup such as links, images as described in the way above, cursive and bold text. 
    > **_NOTE:_** Beware that the implementation of commonmark does **not** support colspan or rowspan and that it is **not** possible either to nest tables. This is because commonmark upholds the standard that tables should be in accordance with 1NF at least. 

- To appear in the Table of Contents in the sidebar a file must be added to the laid out tree structure in `\docs\source\_toc.yml`. This because of the use of the [external_toc](https://sphinx-external-toc.readthedocs.io/en/latest/user_guide/sphinx.html) library, necessary to create a nested tree structure. Next to that, the file needs to contain a level 1 header to be shown in the Table of Contents. Beware, additional level 1 headers in the same file are _ignored_. 

- In case you want to include several files into one file (for example different files with release notes for hotfixes), you can perform the following action:
    ```
        ```{include} <path to a file>
        ```
        ```{include} <path to another file>
        ```
    ```

    > **_NOTE:_** The files that are included into another file cannot have a level 1 header.

- If you want to add a Python library to use in your documentation, you can do so by adding it to the file `requirements.txt` in the root of the repository. Make sure to also include it in the extensions array in `\docs\source\conf.py`.  Then it will be loaded while building the documentation.

- Codeblocks can also be shown inline between single backticks like this \``inline codeblock`\`

## How can I use notes, warnings, etc. in this documentation environment?

To use notes in this documentation environment, you can use the following syntax in a markdown file:
```
    ```{eval-rst}
       .. note::  
            Match rules result in one or more database queries.
    ```
```

The same applies for using warnings with the directive `.. warning::` instead of `.. note::`
